ce:section.ce:para:
PEI grafted GQDs showed an intense absorption band at 360nm (shown as insert (b) in Fig. 5
                           ), which is red shifted compared to pristine GQDs, Table 1
                           . The red shifting could be a result of the larger size of GQDs-PEI compared to pristine GQDs (see Section 3.1.1). The prepared GQDs-PEI shows excellent luminescence properties with a PL quantum yield of 0.88 which was almost two times higher than the pristine GQDs (0.48), Table 1. This is ascribed to the effects of surface passivation of the GQDs as a result of the grafting with PEI. Doping and surface grafting of GQDs have been reported to lead to enhanced fluorescence properties [12]. Thus, the relatively high quantum yield could only mean that the PEI was successfully grafted onto the surfaces of the GQDs as reported previously [11]. The fluorescence lifetime of GQDs-PEI was found to be 9.8ns, which is an increase compared to that recorded for the pristine GQDs (without PEI) (5.6ns), Table 1.
